# Google AI Search + Ads Playbook (Neil Patel Breakdown)

*Source: Neil Patel video on 8 fixes after Google’s AI updates. Interpreted as an internal strategy doc, not a generic summary.*

---

## Big Picture: One Website, Two Systems, One Brain

Historically, most companies split thinking like this:

- SEO team: “We rank pages.”
- Paid team: “We buy traffic.”

Google’s latest AI-driven changes (Performance Max, AI Max for Search, auto-generated assets, URL expansion) ignore that separation.[web:93][web:96][web:99][web:102]  

Google now uses the **same website content** to:

- understand what you do,
- generate ad text and video assets,
- choose landing pages automatically,
- and evaluate conversion performance to steer smart bidding.[web:93][web:96][web:99][web:102]

So every fix you make to your site now affects:

- organic rankings and AI overviews,
- Performance Max (and AI Max) performance and cost per conversion.[web:89][web:93][web:99][web:102]

This video’s eight steps are best understood as:

- Steps 1–4: “Fix what’s broken so AI can actually use your site properly.”
- Steps 5–8: “Build durable advantages that are hard for competitors to copy.”

---

## Step 1 — Make Your Website Fast (Core Web Vitals)

Google’s AI and Smart Bidding rely heavily on **conversion rate**.[web:93][web:99] Slow pages tank conversions and bounce users before anything can happen.  

Google promotes Core Web Vitals as key UX signals: Largest Contentful Paint (LCP), Interaction to Next Paint (INP, replacing FID), and Cumulative Layout Shift (CLS).[web:89][web:91][web:95]

**Why this matters now:**

- If your landing pages take 4–5+ seconds to load, users bounce before converting.[web:90][web:98]
- Smart bidding sees low conversion rate and sends less traffic or pays more per conversion.[web:90][web:93]
- For organic, poor Core Web Vitals can drag rankings.[web:89][web:91][web:95]

**What to actually do:**

1. **Run PageSpeed Insights** on your top landing pages (SEO + ads).[web:88][web:89][web:90]
2. Focus on pages with:
   - LCP > 2.5s,
   - poor INP,
   - high CLS.[web:89][web:90][web:98]
3. Fix the usual bottlenecks:
   - compress/resize images or serve them in next-gen formats (WebP),
   - remove or defer non-critical JavaScript,
   - minify CSS/JS/HTML,
   - simplify heavy hero sections and above-the-fold elements.[web:90][web:92][web:98]

**Core idea:** One speed fix benefits both SEO and ads at the same time.

